{
  "texts": [
    "While an independent confirmation is still missing, the authors promise a speedup of several orders of magnitude compared to traditional finite element solvers [512] 24.",
    "23 The dilation parameter depends on x and thus introduces additional degrees of freedom throughout the domain.",
    "24 After close examination and exchanges with the authors of [506,508,[510][511][512], we have concluded that the current speed-up is mainly attributable to the simultaneously employed reduced order models.",
    "Minor improvements in accuracy are possible through the employed r -adaptivity and convolutions, however, accompanied by an increase in computational effort.",
    "Furthermore, we have been informed that the hiDeNN methodology is implemented most efficiently in the standard finite element way, i.e., without NNs, unlike the descriptions in [506,508,[510][511][512]."
  ]
}